# n8n-decanter ‚Äî guide for coding agents

This is the **source of truth** for working in this repository, and it is written to
be tool-agnostic. Codex and opencode read this file natively; Claude Code reads it
through a one-line `@AGENTS.md` import in `CLAUDE.md`; other agents can be pointed at
this file directly. Keep project-specific rules here so every agent stays in sync.

This repo holds the **Code-node source** of n8n workflows *decanted* into
git-friendly form: one folder per workflow containing a read-only
`workflow.json` structure snapshot plus a `code/` subdir with one source file
per Code node. The `n8n-decanter` CLI syncs the code with the live n8n
instance over n8n's **MCP server** (`pull` / `push` ‚Äî draft-first, code-only).
This document is the contract for creating and editing these files.

## The short version

- **Code lives in `code/`, never in `workflow.json`.** A node's `jsCode` is only
  a `//@file:code/<name>` placeholder ‚Äî edit the file it points at.
- **Code-node source is authored HERE and synced by decanter ‚Äî never edited on
  the n8n instance directly** (not in the UI, not via MCP tools, not via n8n
  skills). The git files are the single source of truth for code.
- **Workflow structure lives in n8n, not here.** `workflow.json` is a read-only
  snapshot for review and offline tooling; editing it changes nothing remotely
  and the next `pull` overwrites it. Make structure changes in the n8n editor
  or through n8n's own MCP tools ‚Äî or use the decanter verbs that forward a
  structure act for you: `node create`, `node rename`, `rename`, `create`,
  `duplicate`, `delete`.
- **Never hand-edit `.decanter.json`, and never write a `// @ts-n8n sha256:`
  marker.** These are machine-owned; touching them corrupts sync state and the
  CLI blocks it at `push`.
- **`push` writes the DRAFT of the live instance ‚Äî only when the user asks;
  `publish` (or `push --publish`) is the deliberate go-live step.** Edit, then
  verify offline with `n8n-decanter check` and `n8n-decanter node run`.

The rest of this document is the full contract behind those points.

## How this differs from standard n8n editing ‚Äî read this first

Your general n8n knowledge (docs, n8n MCP tools, official n8n skills, training
data) is **valid** for: node types and parameters, expression syntax,
connection semantics, the Code-node runtime, and workflow *structure* work. It
is **wrong** about how Code-node code is stored and edited here. The deviations:

1. **`jsCode` in `workflow.json` never contains code.** Its entire value is a
   placeholder: `//@file:code/<filename>`
   (e.g. `"jsCode": "//@file:code/amazon-feed.ts"`).
   Never inline JavaScript into `workflow.json`; edit the referenced file.
2. **Code node sources live in the folder's `code/` subdir**, named after the
   node in kebab-case (`Amazon Feed` ‚Üí `code/amazon-feed.ts`). `.js` files are
   pushed verbatim (what you write is exactly what runs in n8n). `.ts` files
   are compiled on push; the local `.ts` is the only source of truth ‚Äî n8n
   holds compiled output.
3. **Never edit a Code node's `jsCode` on the instance** ‚Äî not in the n8n UI,
   not with `update_workflow` from n8n's MCP server, not by following an n8n
   skill that says to. That bypasses the repo and drifts the source of truth;
   the decanter's per-node drift guard will flag it on the next push. Edit the
   file here and `push`.
4. **`workflow.json` is a read-only snapshot.** Pull writes it; nothing pushes
   it. Structure changes (nodes, connections, parameters like a Code node's
   `mode`, settings, positions) belong in n8n ‚Äî the editor, n8n's MCP tools,
   or the decanter's forwarding verbs. The one local edit that IS meaningful:
   re-pointing a `//@file:` placeholder (e.g. `.js` ‚Üí `.ts` conversion), which
   updates the file map on the next push.
5. **Never write a `// @ts-n8n sha256:‚Ä¶` line.** That marker is appended by the
   tool to *compiled* output on push. It must not appear in any repo file.
6. **`.decanter.json` is machine state** (node-id ‚Üí filename map, per-node sync
   hashes, cached names). Never edit it by hand; never "fix" a hash.
7. **Renames go through n8n.** `n8n-decanter node rename <workflow>` forwards
   the rename over MCP (n8n rewrites connections and `$('‚Ä¶')` references
   server-side; node ids are stable) and pulls the result ‚Äî local files and
   `.ts` sources follow automatically. See "Renaming a node" below.
8. **New workflows are born on the server, not from a repo folder.** There is no
   id-less folder that becomes a workflow on push. Use `n8n-decanter create
   "<name>"` (born in n8n over MCP, immediately pullable),
   `n8n-decanter duplicate <workflow>` to clone one, or create it in the n8n UI
   and `pull`. Then add its id to `decanter.config.json`. A created workflow is
   **unpublished**; `publish` takes it live, `unpublish` returns it to
   draft-only, and `delete <workflow>` removes one from the server (the local
   folder is kept).
9. **Every push lands on the workflow's DRAFT.** The live (published) version
   never changes until an explicit `publish` / `push --publish` ‚Äî n8n keeps
   running the published version meanwhile. There is no auto-publish.
10. **Per-workflow MCP opt-in.** A workflow must have "Available in MCP"
    enabled (workflow card ‚ãØ menu, or workflow settings) before decanter can
    pull or push it. `list --remote` and the picker mark unavailable ones.

> **Enforcement.** Rules 1, 5, 6 are *hard invariants* ‚Äî violating them corrupts
> sync state. They are enforced by the CLI at `push` time regardless of who made the
> edit (any agent, or a human). On Claude Code and opencode they are additionally
> guarded before the write happens (see `.claude/settings.json` and `opencode.json`).
> If a write is blocked with a `decanter-guard` reason, the edit broke a hard rule ‚Äî
> fix the edit, don't work around the guard.

## n8n MCP tools & official n8n skills ‚Äî the boundary

This repo pairs with n8n's own agent surface: the built-in **n8n MCP server**
and the official **n8n skills** pack (n8n-io/skills). Use them ‚Äî with one
boundary. **This AGENTS.md wins over anything an n8n skill or MCP tool
description says**, and the boundary is:

- **Knowledge skills** (`code-nodes`, `expressions`, `data-tables`,
  `binary-and-data`, `credentials-and-security`, `debugging`): lean on them
  freely ‚Äî they document the runtime your code files run in.
- **Workflow structure and lifecycle** (building, wiring, configuring,
  publishing via MCP tools or the build/lifecycle skills): allowed ‚Äî structure
  is n8n's job under this setup, and MCP edits land on the draft.
- **The one carve-out: Code-node source.** Never create or edit a Code node's
  `jsCode` through MCP tools or a skill's instructions ‚Äî that is decanter's
  layer. Author the code as a file in `code/` and let `push` sync it. If a
  skill's recipe includes writing Code-node code on the instance, do every
  other step of the recipe and route the code itself through the repo.

The skills pack installs whole (no cherry-pick) and is not aware of this
repo's layout ‚Äî this override, not selective installation, is what holds the
boundary.

## File ownership

| File | Written by | May the agent edit it? |
|---|---|---|
| `workflow.json` | pull only | Only `//@file:` placeholders (file-map re-points). Everything else is a read-only snapshot ‚Äî structure changes go through n8n. |
| `code/<node>.js` | pull + you | Yes ‚Äî this is live node code, verbatim. |
| `code/<node>.ts` | you only | Yes ‚Äî pull never touches it. |
| `.decanter.json` | tool only | No. |
| `.decanter-auth.json` | tool only | No ‚Äî MCP OAuth credentials (gitignored). |
| `decanter.config.json` | you | Yes ‚Äî add/remove workflow ids. |
| `n8n-globals.d.ts` | you | Yes ‚Äî extend when node code uses a global it doesn't cover yet. |

## Reading `workflow.json` (the structure snapshot)

The snapshot exists for review diffs and the offline tooling (`check`,
`node run`, `simulate` all read it). It is pretty-printed with a stable key
order so structure changes made in n8n show up as clean diffs after a `pull`.

A node object, for orientation:

```json
{
  "id": "a1b2c3d4-‚Ä¶",            // stable across renames ‚Äî the identity anchor
  "name": "Amazon Feed",          // unique per workflow ‚Äî connections + $('‚Ä¶') reference it
  "type": "n8n-nodes-base.code",
  "typeVersion": 2,
  "position": [880, 300],
  "parameters": {
    "mode": "runOnceForAllItems", // or "runOnceForEachItem" ‚Äî set in n8n
    "jsCode": "//@file:code/amazon-feed.ts"
  }
}
```

Connections are keyed by **node name**, not id. Expressions keep their `=`
prefix (`"={{ $json.sku }}"`). None of it is pushable from here ‚Äî a stale
snapshot is refreshed by `pull` (`status` prints a hint when it lags n8n).

### Renaming a node

Use the verb ‚Äî it forwards the rename to n8n over MCP (which rewrites
connections and expression references server-side), rewrites `$('‚Ä¶')` in local
`.ts` sources, and pulls the result so files and placeholders follow:

```sh
n8n-decanter node rename <workflow> "<Old Name>" "<New Name>"
```

Node **ids are stable across renames** ‚Äî the id-keyed `.decanter.json` map is
what keeps each local file attached to its node, whoever renames it (this
verb, the n8n UI, or another agent via MCP). A rename made *outside* decanter
is picked up by the next `pull` the same way.

Renaming a **workflow**: `n8n-decanter rename <workflow> "<New Name>"` ‚Äî
forwarded to n8n immediately. The folder is a stable local slug and is left
untouched; the display name is cached in `.decanter.json`.

### Adding a Code node

1. `n8n-decanter node create <workflow> "<Node name>" [--ts]` creates it **in
   n8n** (over MCP, with a runnable starter body) and pulls it back: the
   `code/` source file, the `//@file:` placeholder, and the `.decanter.json`
   entry all land in one step. The node arrives **disconnected**.
2. Wire it up in n8n (editor or MCP tools ‚Äî wiring is structure), then `pull`
   to refresh the snapshot. Edit the source in `code/`.
3. Verify: `n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture.json]` to execute it, then
   `n8n-decanter check` (typecheck + layout).

## Writing Code node code

The runtime contract (identical for `.js` and `.ts` ‚Äî types are erased):

- Code runs as a function body, **top-level `return` required**.
  - `runOnceForAllItems`: return an array of items: `[{ json: {‚Ä¶} }, ‚Ä¶]`.
    Always wrap in `{ json: ‚Ä¶ }` explicitly.
  - `runOnceForEachItem`: return a single `{ json: {‚Ä¶} }`.
  - Editors squiggle that top-level `return`/`await` (TS1108/TS1375/TS1378) ‚Äî
    a **false positive** from the editor's own tsserver; ignore it, and never
    "fix" it by wrapping the file in a function. `n8n-decanter check` wraps
    node bodies in memory before typechecking and is authoritative.
    The bundled `decanter-ts-plugin/` suppresses exactly these three codes on
    node files (all other diagnostics stay live) once tsserver runs the
    workspace TypeScript: `npm install`, then in VS Code accept
    *Use Workspace Version* (offered via `.vscode/settings.json`'s
    `typescript.tsdk`; JetBrains uses the project TypeScript by default).
- **Available globals: `n8n-globals.d.ts` is the authoritative list.** Open it
  to see every global in scope with its exact signature (`$input`, `$('Node
  Name')`, `$json`, `$binary`, the Luxon `DateTime`/`$now`/`$today`, `$workflow`,
  `$execution`, `$getWorkflowStaticData`, ‚Ä¶). If node code needs a global that
  file doesn't declare yet, add it there.
- **Imports**: `.js` nodes ‚Äî none at all (they run verbatim; assume the
  instance allows no external or built-in modules). `.ts` nodes ‚Äî imports
  from inside this repo (`shared/`, relative paths) and from npm packages
  listed in `decanter.config.json`'s `"bundleDependencies"` are **bundled
  into the compiled node on push** (self-contained output, works on any
  instance incl. n8n Cloud). Rules: imports at the **top of the file** only;
  relative paths must stay inside this repo; unlisted npm packages and Node
  builtins (`node:*`, `fs`, `crypto`, ‚Ä¶) are compile errors. Never
  `require()`.
- `console.log` is available for debugging (visible in the execution view).
- `$('Node Name')` takes the node's **name** ‚Äî so `node rename` keeps it in sync.

### `.js` nodes (default ‚Äî lossless)

What you write is byte-for-byte what runs and what round-trips back on pull.
Type-safety via JSDoc:

```js
// @ts-check

/** @typedef {{ sku: string, qty: number }} StockLine */

/** @type {StockLine[]} */
const lines = [];
for (const item of $input.all()) {
  // ‚Ä¶
}
return lines.map((l) => ({ json: l }));
```

- First line is `// @ts-check`.
- Prefer `@typedef` for shapes, inline casts `/** @type {Foo} */ (x)` where
  narrowing is needed. `@template`, `@satisfies` are available.
- Comments are fine and encouraged ‚Äî they survive into n8n and document the
  node in place.

### `.ts` nodes (one-way)

Choose `.ts` when the type surface is heavy (large interfaces, generics,
discriminated unions). Costs, so you can weigh them:

- esbuild compiles on push: **comments are stripped** and **line numbers shift**
  ‚Äî n8n error line numbers won't match the source, and the node code in the
  n8n UI is undocumented output. Documentation belongs in the `.ts`.
- Instance-side edits can't be merged back automatically ‚Äî `pull` warns and
  `status --diff` shows what changed remotely; port it into the `.ts` by hand
  (the next push overwrites the remote edit).

Rules: full TS is fine (interfaces, type aliases, enums, generics); still
ends in a top-level `return`. Never commit compiled output; never add the
marker line.

**Shared code (`shared/`)**: put helpers and types used by several nodes in
`shared/*.ts` and import them from `.ts` nodes ‚Äî types *and* functions:

```ts
import { total, type OrderLine } from "../../shared/money";

const lines: OrderLine[] = $input.all().map((i) => i.json as OrderLine);
return [{ json: { total: total(lines) } }];
```

Push inlines the imported code into the compiled node (each importing node
carries its own copy ‚Äî keep helpers small). Editing a shared file makes every
importing node show up as "push pending" in `status`; push to propagate.
Small npm libraries work the same way once installed here (`npm i zod`) and
opted in via `"bundleDependencies": ["zod"]` in `decanter.config.json` ‚Äî
pure-JS packages only (no native addons, no builtins). `.js` nodes cannot
import; give them JSDoc `@typedef`s or convert to `.ts`.

### Switching a node `.js` ‚Üí `.ts` (or back)

1. Rename the file, convert JSDoc ‚Üî annotations.
2. Update the `//@file:` placeholder in `workflow.json` (the one meaningful
   local edit there ‚Äî it re-points the file map).
3. `n8n-decanter check`. The tool picks up the new extension on next push;
   direction of sync changes accordingly (`.ts` = one-way).

## Verification

Two offline tools, always available (no credentials, no network, no live n8n):

- **`n8n-decanter check`** ‚Äî runs the layout-compliance guard *and* the
  typecheck (the same wrapper that maps top-level-`return` node bodies back to
  real line numbers). Run it after editing any code file or `n8n-globals.d.ts`;
  treat a failure as a blocker. `npm run typecheck` is an alias for it.
- **`n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture.json]`** ‚Äî actually executes a node's body
  against a faked n8n context (`$input`, `$json`, `$('Node')`, `DateTime`, ‚Ä¶) and
  prints the items it returns. Prefer this over hand-rolling a throwaway test
  script.
  - The optional fixture JSON supplies the context; every field is optional:

    ```json
    {
      "input":  [{ "json": { "sku": "A1" } }],
      "nodes":  { "Fetch Products": [{ "json": { "id": 1 } }] },
      "env":    { "REGION": "eu" },
      "staticData": { "global": { "cursor": 42 } }
    }
    ```

    `input` feeds `$input`/`$json`; `nodes` backs `$('Node Name')`; without a
    fixture the input defaults to a single empty item. `env` backs `$env`,
    which is **empty by default** (like n8n's scoped `$env`) ‚Äî set it here, or
    pass `--allow-env` to inherit the process environment (may include
    `N8N_API_KEY`; never `run --allow-env` an untrusted node).
    `$getWorkflowStaticData` is seeded from `workflow.json`'s `staticData`
    (`global` and this node's `node:` slice); a fixture `staticData` replaces
    the matching slice (`"node"` = the node being run). Mutations are visible
    during the run but never persisted ‚Äî `run` is offline.
  - Run mode (`runOnceForAllItems` / `runOnceForEachItem`) is read from the node
    in `workflow.json`, so each-item nodes are looped once per input item.
- JSON validity of `workflow.json` after every structural edit.

## Real execution data (`executions/` ‚Äî temporary, gitignored)

When you need to see what data actually flows through a workflow ‚Äî to write an
accurate `node run` fixture, or to debug a node against real payloads ‚Äî fetch
recent executions from the instance instead of guessing shapes:

```sh
n8n-decanter executions "<workflow>"                    # 5 most recent, full run data
n8n-decanter executions "<workflow>" --status=error --limit=3
n8n-decanter executions 4711                            # one execution by its id
```

Each execution lands as `workflows/<folder>/executions/<execId>.json`. The items
a node produced are under
`data.resultData.runData["<Node Name>"][0].data.main[0][]` ‚Äî each entry's
`.json` is one item, exactly what `$('<Node Name>')` (and the downstream node's
`$input`) sees at runtime. Copy real item shapes from here into `node run` fixtures.

Rules:

- **Temporary working data, never committed.** The tool writes the dir
  self-ignoring (`executions/.gitignore` containing `*`) because run data can
  hold credentials and PII ‚Äî never weaken that, and never copy secrets from it
  into code or fixtures.
- **Clean up when the task that needed it is done:**
  `n8n-decanter executions clean` (offline; removes every `executions/` dir,
  or pass a workflow ref to scope it).
- **Convenience, not ground truth.** Executions run the *published* workflow
  version (n8n 2.x), which may be older than the local draft, and payloads
  change over time ‚Äî re-fetch rather than trusting stale files.
- These fetches use the n8n **public API key** (`N8N_API_KEY`) ‚Äî the one
  surface MCP doesn't cover. Without a key configured the verb says so.

## Filling simulation gaps (`mocks/` ‚Äî committed scenarios)

`n8n-decanter simulate <workflow>` replays a workflow through a real n8n engine,
pinning network nodes to a captured execution. A **gap** is a network node the
replay reaches that has **no captured data** (added or reparametrized since the
capture). `simulate` hard-errors on a gap rather than run half-real ‚Äî and this
is a task you, the agent, are well-suited to complete. **The CLI never calls an
LLM or needs an API key; you author the mock data locally.**

The loop:

```sh
n8n-decanter "<workflow>" simulate --execution <id>      # ‚úó gap: <Node> has no data
n8n-decanter "<workflow>" mock create "<slug>" --execution <id>   # writes a committed, fillable scenario
#   ‚Üí edit workflows/<folder>/mocks/<slug>.json  (see below)
n8n-decanter "<workflow>" mock check <slug>              # validate offline (fast, no Docker)
n8n-decanter "<workflow>" simulate --mock <slug>         # replay the filled scenario
```

`mock create` copies the capture into `mocks/<slug>.json` (a **named scenario** ‚Äî
`happy-path`, `empty-cart`, ‚Ä¶; the slug defaults to the execution id) and adds a
`_decanterMock` block listing each gap node with its **type**, **parameters**,
and an **`inputSample`** (the items feeding it). For each node in `fill`, add its
output under `data.resultData.runData`:

```jsonc
"data": { "resultData": { "runData": {
  // ‚Ä¶existing captured nodes stay untouched‚Ä¶
  "<Node Name>": [                    // one entry per run (a normal node runs once)
    { "data": { "main": [             // outputs; index 0 is the node's main output
      [                               // items array for that output
        { "json": { /* the realistic output this node would emit */ } }
      ]
    ] } }
  ]
} } }
```

How to author good data:

- **Use the context.** Read the node's `type`/`parameters` and `inputSample` in
  the `_decanterMock.fill` entry, and infer a realistic output. An HTTP GET to a
  CRM returns a record; a DB query returns rows; a Slack post returns a
  message-sent ack. One item in, one enriched item out is the common case.
- **Match the input's `pairedItem` when downstream nodes link items** (e.g.
  `$('<Node>').itemMatching(...)`): give each output item `"pairedItem": { "item": <inputIndex> }`.
- **Keep the `fill` list as-is.** It records which nodes are mocked (not
  captured) and is what `mock check` validates. Don't delete it.
- **Validate offline with `mock check <slug>`** ‚Äî a fast, node-named structural
  check that needs no Docker; run it in your fill‚Üícheck‚Üífix loop. It fails if an
  item isn't `{ "json": ‚Ä¶ }` or a `fill` node is still empty. `simulate --mock`
  runs the same check on load. There is no official n8n JSON Schema ‚Äî this is the
  decanter's own check of the exact shape it replays.
- **Committed, so review for PII.** Unlike `executions/`, `mocks/` is tracked in
  git (reproducible replays). The data you write is *mock*, but the copied
  capture around it can hold real payloads ‚Äî don't commit secrets.

## Data tables (`data-tables/` ‚Äî temporary, gitignored)

When a workflow reads or writes an n8n **data table** (the built-in
project-scoped tables, n8n ‚â• 2.x) and you need to see what's actually in it ‚Äî
its columns or its rows ‚Äî fetch it instead of guessing:

```sh
n8n-decanter data-tables                                # every table: schema + rows
n8n-decanter data-tables "Orders"                       # one table by name (or id)
n8n-decanter data-tables "Orders" --filter '{"type":"and","filters":[{"columnName":"status","condition":"eq","value":"active"}]}'
n8n-decanter data-tables "Orders" --search foo --sort total:desc --limit 50 --all
```

Data tables are **project-scoped, not owned by a workflow**, so they land in a
single **top-level `data-tables/` dir** (next to `decanter.config.json`), not
under a workflow folder. Each table becomes
`data-tables/<table-slug>/{meta,columns,rows}.json` ‚Äî `columns.json` is the
schema, `rows.json` the (possibly filtered) rows, and `meta.json` records the id,
name, and the applied filter/search/sort/limit + row count, so a filtered
`rows.json` is never mistaken for the whole table.

Rules:

- **Read-only.** The CLI only ever *reads* data tables ‚Äî it never creates,
  updates, or deletes a table, column, or row. (n8n's MCP tools cannot read
  rows at all ‚Äî this verb rides the public API key, which is why it needs
  `N8N_API_KEY`.)
- **Temporary working data, never committed.** The dir is written self-ignoring
  (`data-tables/.gitignore` containing `*`) because tables can hold PII ‚Äî never
  weaken that, and never copy secrets from it into code or fixtures.
- **Pull a slice, not the whole table.** For large tables use `--filter` (a JSON
  string of conditions, passed straight to the API), `--search` (free text),
  and `--sort` (`col:asc|desc`) to narrow rows server-side; `--limit` caps a page
  (default 100, max 250) and `--all` follows the cursor to exhaust the result.
- **Clean up when done:** `n8n-decanter data-tables clean` (offline; removes the
  whole `data-tables/` dir).
- **Config-gated.** Available when `"dataTables"` is on in `decanter.config.json`
  (its default); if it's `false` the fetch refuses (`clean` still works).

## Commands ‚Äî who runs what

- **Offline, safe ‚Äî run freely:** `n8n-decanter check` (or `npm run typecheck`),
  `n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture]`,
  `n8n-decanter mock create <workflow>` / `mock check <workflow>` (fillable mock scenarios),
  `n8n-decanter executions clean`, `n8n-decanter data-tables clean`. These never
  touch the network.
- **Reads remote, no writes:** `n8n-decanter status` (`--diff` shows the line
  diffs; exits 1 on code conflict/remote code drift), `n8n-decanter list
  --remote` (marks workflows not yet available in MCP), `n8n-decanter
  executions <workflow>` (fetches execution data, read-only), and `n8n-decanter
  data-tables [table‚Ä¶]` (fetches data-table schema + rows, read-only) ‚Äî safe to
  run, but they do contact the instance.
- **Live n8n instance ‚Äî only when the user explicitly asks:** `n8n-decanter
  pull` / `push` / `watch` sync code with the real instance (pushes land on
  the **draft**); `create "<name>"` adds a new workflow, `duplicate <workflow>`
  clones one, `node create` / `node rename` / `rename` forward structure acts
  to n8n; `publish` / `unpublish` change what is live (`publish` takes the
  draft live, `unpublish` returns it to draft-only; `push --publish` combines
  the two). Otherwise finish edits, verify with `check` + `run`, and report
  that the change is ready to push (or publish).
- **Destructive ‚Äî never without an explicit instruction:** `n8n-decanter <ref>
  delete` removes a workflow from the server (hard delete via the public API,
  even if published; the local folder is kept as the git record). Run it only
  when the user has clearly asked to delete that specific workflow; it prompts
  for `y/N` and needs `--force` to run non-interactively.
- Never use `--force` on push without the user's explicit instruction ‚Äî it
  overrides the per-node drift guard that protects code edits made on the
  instance. (On `delete`, `--force` instead means "skip the confirmation" ‚Äî
  same rule: only on an explicit instruction.)
- **Credentials:** MCP (OAuth via `init`, or `N8N_MCP_TOKEN`) powers the sync
  and structure verbs; the optional public API key (`N8N_API_KEY`) powers
  `executions`, `data-tables`, `duplicate`, and `delete`.
